Use ASP.NET Core's **`WebApplicationFactory<TEntryPoint>`** — it hosts your app in-memory and gives you an `HttpClient` that talks to it without opening a real port.

**Setup:**

```csharp
// MyMcpTests.cs
public class McpIntegrationTests : IClassFixture<WebApplicationFactory<Program>>
{
    private readonly HttpClient _client;

    public McpIntegrationTests(WebApplicationFactory<Program> factory)
    {
        _client = factory.CreateClient();
    }

    [Fact]
    public async Task Initialize_ReturnsCapabilities()
    {
        var request = new
        {
            jsonrpc = "2.0",
            id = 1,
            method = "initialize",
            @params = new
            {
                protocolVersion = "2025-03-26",
                capabilities = new { },
                clientInfo = new { name = "test-client", version = "1.0" }
            }
        };

        var response = await _client.PostAsJsonAsync("/mcp", request);

        response.EnsureSuccessStatusCode();
        var body = await response.Content.ReadFromJsonAsync<JsonElement>();
        Assert.Equal("2.0", body.GetProperty("jsonrpc").GetString());
        Assert.Equal(1, body.GetProperty("id").GetInt32());
        Assert.True(body.GetProperty("result").TryGetProperty("capabilities", out _));
    }

    [Fact]
    public async Task ToolsList_ReturnsRegisteredTools()
    {
        // Initialize first
        await InitializeAsync();

        var request = new { jsonrpc = "2.0", id = 2, method = "tools/list" };
        var response = await _client.PostAsJsonAsync("/mcp", request);

        response.EnsureSuccessStatusCode();
        var body = await response.Content.ReadFromJsonAsync<JsonElement>();
        var tools = body.GetProperty("result").GetProperty("tools");
        Assert.True(tools.GetArrayLength() > 0);
    }

    private async Task InitializeAsync() { /* send initialize + initialized */ }
}
```

**Key techniques:**

| Need | Approach |
|---|---|
| Override services (mock DB, etc.) | `factory.WithWebHostBuilder(b => b.ConfigureServices(...))` |
| Test SSE transport | Use `_client.GetStreamAsync("/sse")` and read the event stream |
| Test tool invocation | Send `tools/call` JSON-RPC and assert the `result.content` |
| Test error cases | Assert `error.code` and `error.message` on the JSON-RPC response |

**For SSE (Streamable HTTP):**

```csharp
[Fact]
public async Task Sse_ReceivesEvents()
{
    var request = new HttpRequestMessage(HttpMethod.Post, "/mcp");
    request.Headers.Accept.Add(new("text/event-stream"));
    request.Content = JsonContent.Create(new
    {
        jsonrpc = "2.0", id = 1, method = "initialize",
        @params = new { protocolVersion = "2025-03-26", capabilities = new { },
                        clientInfo = new { name = "test", version = "1.0" } }
    });

    var response = await _client.SendAsync(request,
        HttpCompletionOption.ResponseHeadersRead);
    using var stream = await response.Content.ReadAsStreamAsync();
    using var reader = new StreamReader(stream);

    var line = await reader.ReadLineAsync();
    Assert.StartsWith("event:", line);
}
```

**Package needed:** `Microsoft.AspNetCore.Mvc.Testing` — add it to your test project. Make sure `Program` is accessible (add `InternalsVisibleTo` or a partial class).
